<br>
i always have to wonder one thing....<br>
<br>
why is there the automatic assumption that just because one farms, one cant really play their class? =)<br>
<br>
i suppose i fit the definition of &quot;farmer drooid&quot; quite well.  im a solo player, i prefer to solo and hunt alone (classic anti-social druid type personality), i genuinely enjoy playing in lower level zones and wandering around killing things and collecting little goodies for my twinkage pile.  i really like farming things for my tradeskills and quests, dont mind sitting around for hours on end killin little things or waiting on other things to spawn.<br>
<br>
and this solo life ive undertaken for most of my druidic career taught me how to be a better druid.  i learned the layout of dungeons, agro control, pathing and agro, game mechanics, all by playing by myself, all by RELYING on myself.  a solo druid has no cleric to heal them or tank to taunt off them, has no monk to solo pull for them or wizard to power nuke.  a solo druid does it all on their own.<br>
<br>
so lets just drop this &quot;i'm a real druid and they're just a twink/farmer&quot; holier-than-thou attitude.  its way too reminiscent of the nasty attitudes so many old rogues had/have against any &quot;new&quot; rogues/twinks/druids.  we are all just people playing characters, regardless of how we play or how WELL we play, and regardless of what class button we happen to have clicked first. <p>-K<br>
